label.value: Uterine Corpus Mixed Epithelial and Mesenchymal Neoplasm

value.value: A primary, benign or malignant neoplasm of the uterine corpus characterized by the presence of an epithelial and a mesenchymal component. Representative examples include adenomyoma, adenosarcoma, and carcinosarcoma.
An uncommon malignant neoplasm arising from the uterine corpus. It is characterized by the presence of a malignant epithelial component and a benign mesenchymal (usually fibrous) component.
A non-neoplastic trophoblastic disorder characterized by the presence of remnants of intermediate trophoblasts in the uterine cavity and infrequently the fallopian tube from a previous pregnancy.
A category of non-neoplastic gestational trophoblastic disorders that includes the exaggerated placental site reaction and placental site nodule or plaque. It does not include hydatidiform mole.
The largest part of the brain composed of the cerebral hemispheres, thalamus, hypothalamus, and the limbic system.
A finger or toe in human beings or corresponding part in other vertebrates.
A variant of cervical squamous cell carcinoma characterized by the presence of keratin pearls. Intercellular bridges and cytoplasmic keratinization are usually present.

A variant of cervical squamous cell carcinoma characterized by the presence of polygonal squamous cells. Intercellular bridges and cytoplasmic keratinization may be present, but keratin pearls are absent.
An aggressive variant of cervical squamous cell carcinoma characterized by the presence of nests of malignant basaloid squamous cells with scant amount of cytoplasm.

label.value: Breast Paget Disease and Intraductal Carcinoma

value.value: Paget disease of the breast associated with the presence of a usually high grade ductal carcinoma in situ in the lactiferous glands.

A highly differentiated variant of cervical squamous cell carcinoma characterized by the presence of a warty surface and stromal invasion with pushing borders. The malignant cells have abundant cytoplasm and minimal nuclear atypia. Koilocytosis is not present.
A human papillomavirus-related cervical squamous cell carcinoma characterized by the presence of a warty surface and koilocytotic atypia.

A human papillomavirus-related cervical squamous cell carcinoma characterized by the presence of papillary structures covered with epithelial cells which show features of cervical intraepithelial neoplasia. The malignant cellular component below the papillary structures is a squamous cell carcinoma.
A variant of cervical squamous cell carcinoma characterized by the presence of islands of cells with uniform, vesicular nuclei and prominent nucleoli and a dense lymphocytic infiltrate.

A human papillomavirus-related cervical squamous cell carcinoma characterized by the presence of papillary structures with fibrovascular cores. It is covered with multiple layers of atypical cells that resemble cervical intraepithelial neoplasia 3.

A benign, precancerous, or malignant neoplasm that arises from the squamous epithelium of the cervix. Representative examples include condyloma acuminatum, cervical intraepithelial neoplasia, and squamous cell carcinoma.

label.value: Low Grade Cervical Squamous Intraepithelial Neoplasia

value.value: A precancerous neoplastic process that affects the cervical squamous epithelium without evidence of invasion. It is usually associated with human papillomavirus infection. It is characterized by the presence of mild atypia in the superficial epithelial layer that may be associated with koilocytosis. Maturation is present in the upper two thirds of the epithelium. Mitotic figures are not numerous and are present in the basal third of the epithelium.

label.value: High Grade Cervical Squamous Intraepithelial Neoplasia

value.value: A precancerous neoplastic process that affects the cervical squamous epithelium. It is usually associated with human papillomavirus infection. It is classified as cervical squamous intraepithelial neoplasia 2 when there is nuclear atypia in both the upper and lower epithelial layers, mitotic figures are confined to the basal two-thirds of the epithelium, and maturation is present in the upper half of the epithelium. It is classified as cervical squamous intraepithelial neoplasia 3 when there is nuclear atypia and mitotic figures throughout the entire thickness of the epithelium, and maturation is absent or confined to the upper third of the epithelium.

Cervical squamous intraepithelial neoplasia characterized by the presence of maturation in the upper half of the squamous epithelium and conspicuous nuclear atypia which is present in all epithelial layers.  Mitotic figures are present in the basal two thirds of the epithelium.

Cervical squamous intraepithelial neoplasia characterized by the presence of maturation in the upper two-thirds of the squamous epithelium and mild nuclear atypia which is present in all epithelial layers.  Mitotic figures are present in the basal third of the epithelium.

An inorganic compound used as a reagent in molecular biology.  As a reagent for peptide mapping and amino acid sequence analysis, cyanogen bromide hydrolyzes peptide bonds at methionine residues in peptides and proteins.  In addition, this agent acts as a coupling reagent for phosphoramidate or pyrophosphate inter-nucleotide bonds in DNA duplexes. (NCI)
A conventional osteosarcoma characterized by the presence of spindle shaped cells.

A usually solitary polypoid lesion that arises from the cervix. It usually affects women in their reproductive years. It is characterized by the presence of a connective tissue core and overlying epithelium.
A rare adenocarcinoma that arises from the cervix. It is characterized by the presence of papillary patterns and cellular budding. Psammoma bodies are often seen.
A cervical mucinous adenocarcinoma characterized by the presence of malignant glandular cells that resemble those of the endocervix.
A cervical mucinous adenocarcinoma that resembles a large intestinal adenocarcinoma.

label.value: Cervical Mucinous Adenocarcinoma, Signet Ring Cell-Type

value.value: A rare cervical mucinous adenocarcinoma characterized by the presence of signet ring cells.
Cervical adenocarcinoma characterized by the presence of gastric differentiation. It is not associated with human papillomavirus infection.
Variation in the number of copies of a particular sequence within the genetic material of an individual. Large-scale copy number polymorphisms are common and widely distributed in the human genome.
A cervical adenocarcinoma characterized by the presence of a prominent villoglandular pattern.
An osteosarcoma characterised by the presence of atypical cartilage of variable cellularity.  It may or may not be associated with the presence of myxoid areas or focal bone formation.

A benign, malignant, or precancerous neoplasm that arises from the glandular epithelium of the cervix. Representative examples include endocervical polyp, cervical adenocarcinoma, and cervical glandular intraepithelial neoplasia.

A genomic microarray-based method able to identify regions in the cancer genome that have undergone copy number fluctuation. This method is reported to be highly sensitive and quantitative, able to detect loss of a single allele. See: Genome Res. 2003 Oct;13(10):2291-305. Epub 2003 Sep 15.

A poorly differentiated variant of adenosquamous carcinoma that arises from the cervix. It is characterized by the presence of large malignant cells with ground glass cytoplasm and stromal eosinophilic infiltrates.
A rare low grade carcinoma that arises from the cervix. It is characterized by the presence of nests of basaloid cells with focal glandular formations.
A rare, aggressive neuroendocrine carcinoma that arises from the cervix and is characterized by the presence of malignant cells with abundant cytoplasm, large nuclei, and prominent nucleoli.
A rare, benign, papillary neoplasm that arises from the cervix. It is characterized by the presence of a fibrovascular core covered by mucinous epithelial cells.
A benign or malignant mesenchymal neoplasm of the cervix.  Representative examples include rhabdomyoma, alveolar soft part sarcoma, and AIDS-related Kaposi sarcoma.

label.value: Uterine Corpus Endometrial Stromal and Related Neoplasms

value.value: A category of benign or malignant mesenchymal neoplasms that arises from the uterine corpus. This category includes the endometrial stromal nodule which is benign and non-invasive, the endometrial stromal sarcoma, and the undifferentiated uterine sarcoma. The endometrial stromal sarcoma is an invasive malignant neoplasm, further subdivided into low grade and high grade endometrial stromal sarcoma. Undifferentiated uterine sarcoma was previously also known as high grade endometrial stromal sarcoma. In 2014, high grade endometrial stromal sarcoma was reclassified and is currently considered a distinct and rare neoplasm. It appears to have a prognosis that falls between low grade endometrial stromal sarcoma and undifferentiated sarcoma.

label.value: Cervical Endometrioid Stromal and Related Neoplasms

value.value: A category of rare neoplasms that arise from the cervix.  It includes low grade endometrioid stromal sarcoma and undifferentiated endocervical sarcoma.
A uterine corpus sarcoma originating from the endometrial stroma. It is further subdivided into low grade and high grade endometrial stromal sarcoma.

A form of melanoma occurring most often on the plantar, palmar, subungual, and periungual skin.  It presents as a pigmented macular lesion with irregular borders.  Morphologically, it consists of atypical spindled and dendritic melanocytes.  The epidermis is often hyperplastic and there is pagetoid infiltration of the epidermis by anaplastic cells.

label.value: Endometrioid Stromal Sarcoma of the Cervix

value.value: A rare sarcoma that arises from the cervix.  This category includes low grade endometrioid stromal sarcoma and undifferentiated endocervical sarcoma.

label.value: Cervical Low Grade Endometrioid Stromal Sarcoma

value.value: A very rare sarcoma that arises from the cervix and is characterized by the presence of cells that resemble endometrial stromal cells.

label.value: Uterine Corpus Low Grade Endometrial Stromal Sarcoma

value.value: A rare, indolent, invasive mesenchymal tumor that arises from the endometrial stroma. It is characterized by the presence of a plexiform vasculature, infrequent mitoses, and insignificant cytologic atypia. Late recurrences may occur.
A high grade undifferentiated sarcoma that arises from the endocervix.
An alveolar soft part sarcoma arising from the cervix.

label.value: Cervical Mixed Epithelial and Mesenchymal Neoplasm

value.value: A benign or malignant neoplasm that arises from the cervix and is characterized by the presence of epithelial and mesenchymal elements. This category includes adenofibroma, adenomyoma, adenosarcoma, and carcinosarcoma.

label.value: Benign Cervical Mixed Epithelial and Mesenchymal Neoplasm

value.value: A neoplasm that arises from the cervix and is characterized by the presence of benign epithelial and benign mesenchymal elements. This category includes adenofibroma and adenomyoma.
